pr_review_comment_body:
When I started coding and testing the fixtures I noticed that the fixtures needed different test methods may need different configurations. For example, some tests need a consumer with `auto_offset_reset=earliest` while others need `auto_offset_reset=latest`.

One way to enable that flexibility would be to let each test to explicitly instantiate the fixtures, without using pytest injection. Another way, would be to provide the pytest fixtures the parameters for each instantiation.

These setters were my way to implement that. Using those, the tests could be coded like this:
```
@set_params(simple_consumer={'auto_offset_reset':'earliest'})
def test_consumer_with_earliest(simple_consumer):
    ...

@set_params(simple_consumer={'auto_offset_reset':'latest'})
def test_consumer_with_latest(simple_consumer):
    ...
```
The parameters set this way are exposed to the fixture method as an injected parameter:
```
@pytest.fixture
def simple_consumer(...some_params..., simple_consumer_params):
    ....
```
Which I though to be simpler and easier to code than handle explicit instantiation and destruction on each test method.

This works only for fixtures with `function` scope.

Thoughts?

